,"Deflection towards tallest row causes hyperpolarisation","Direction of deflection has no effect on membrane potential","Deflection in any direction causes depolarisation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen stereocilia are \u003Cstrong\u003Edeflected towards the tallest row\u003C/strong\u003E, tip links between the stereocilia are stretched, opening mechanically-gated cation channels. This allows potassium and calcium ions to enter the cell, causing depolarisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeflection in any direction causes hyperpolarisation\u003C/strong\u003E - Movement direction specifically determines whether depolarisation or hyperpolarisation occurs, not all movements cause hyperpolarisation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeflection towards tallest row causes hyperpolarisation\u003C/strong\u003E - This movement actually causes depolarisation through cation influx, not hyperpolarisation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirection of deflection has no effect on membrane potential\u003C/strong\u003E - The direction of stereocilia movement is crucial in determining the electrical response of the hair cell.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeflection in any direction causes depolarisation\u003C/strong\u003E - Only deflection towards the tallest row causes depolarisation, while movement away results in hyperpolarisation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen stereocilia are deflected away from the tallest row, the mechanically-gated channels close, preventing cation entry and causing hyperpolarisation. This directional sensitivity is fundamental to how hair cells encode mechanical stimuli into electrical signals.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hair cell stereocilia deflection towards the tallest row opens mechanically-gated ion channels, causing depolarisation.","Hair cell stereocilia deflection away from the tallest row closes mechanically-gated ion channels, causing hyperpolarisation.","The direction of stereocilia movement determines whether the hair cell will depolarise or hyperpolarise."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57567"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17711"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57567"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T22:29:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T22:29:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10425"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72097"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving 